Blockchain and smart contracts in supply chain management: A game
theoretic model
Pietro De Giovanni
Luiss University, Rome, Italy

ARTICLE

INFO

Keywords:
Supply chain management
Blockchains
Smart contracts
Online platforms
Revenue sharing contract
Risk analysis
Game theory

ABSTRACT
This paper proposes a supply chain game that is composed of two firms, one supplier and one retailer. The
supplier sells goods to the retailer and sets the service strategy efforts. The retailer determines the optimal
quantity to purchase and the selling price. The supply chain can be managed through either a traditional
online platform or a blockchain. In the former, firms face business risks due to delivery and service and also
pay high transaction costs. In the latter, they work on a blockchain platform, remove all risks over the supply
chain, and save the transaction costs. However, the blockchain requires initial implementation investments as
well as variable costs. Furthermore, the firms gain in terms of visibility, transparency, and security, which are
summarized in tokens. We identify the conditions and the stochastic cases in which the blockchain is not worth
implementing. Then, we investigate the suitability of a smart wholesale price contract and a smart revenue
sharing contract to better coordinate firms’ relationships and negotiations. We highlight all cases in which
the use of smart contracts makes blockchain applications more operationally convenient and economically
appealing.

1. Introduction
The recent digital transformation that firms and supply chains have
experienced through Industry 4.0 technologies poses important strategic considerations and economic implications. The adoption of Industry
4.0 technologies has been both fashionable and appealing in recent
years due to their potential benefits and the role that they play in the
digital worlds (Ivanov et al., 2019a,b; Frank et al., 2019). However,
firms and supply chains require further analysis to better understand
such rapid and increasing trends, specifically, whether Industry 4.0
technologies supply real operational advantages and concrete market
opportunities (Hofmann and Rüsch, 2017; Liu and De Giovanni, 2019)
or whether their adoption is only a contemporary tendency inspired
by the current technological progress and incentivized by generous
government development plans (Liao et al., 2017; Kiel et al., 2017). In
any case, it seems clear that firms and supply chains need a comprehensive analysis of the strategic behavioral changes required to properly
select and use Industry 4.0 technologies, an accurate estimation of their
economic outcomes, and a careful assessment of the implications for the
whole supply chain (Ivanov et al., 2019a,b; Saberi et al., 2019a; Ivanov
et al., 2016).
One popular technology that can effectively enable all Industry
4.0 applications in Supply Chain (SC) Management is the blockchain
(Kshetri, 2018). A blockchain consists of a set of digital applications
enabling firms and SCs to track, trace, and verify how goods tran-

sit and move along the supply (Casey and Wong, 2017), from the
manufacturers to retailers through distribution centers and logistics
facilities (Cole et al., 2019). Such shared information on a blockchain
platforms allows all supply chain members to be updated, integrated,
and involved in any transaction (Pournader et al., 2019). Today, SCs
are geographically very extended and dispersed, making the boundaries
of their business and competition difficult to even identify (Saberi
et al., 2019a). In addition to the intricate network of relationships
that firms can establish worldwide and that are complicated by the
use of Industry 4.0 technologies, issues like inefficient transactions and
suppliers’ performance, frauds and fake deals, cultural barriers and language differences, international regulations and legislative constraints,
lack of trust and commitment of some suppliers call for additional
information visibility, transparency, and verifiability to better manage
and control the supply chain network, remove all potential business
risks and mitigate the inefficient transactions characterizing the SC
linkages (Dolgui et al., 2019). Blockchains enable trustless networks,
because the parties can transact even though they do not trust each
other (Christidis and Devetsikiotis, 2016) .
Currently, SCs use traditional Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP)
along with online platforms to manage the flows of goods, information,
and money. However, these Information Systems (IS) solutions cannot

