To overcome the traditional IS limitations, firms and SCs can effectively use blockchain applications and pursue their digital transformation (Chakrabarti and Chaudhuri, 2017). Accurate analysis and
overall assessment of blockchain applications embrace both the positive
advantages and the negative implications for business, management,
operations, SCs and stakeholders (Cole et al., 2019). To achieve this
goal, this paper investigates the firms’ convenience of moving from a
traditional online platform to a blockchain application for managing SC
transactions. We start from a simple SC composed of one supplier and
one retailer, negotiating through an online system. The supplier informs
of its availability to sell products at a certain wholesale price; the
retailer decides the number of goods to be purchased from the supplier
and sets the selling price. The supplier takes care of all the post-sale
activities by investing in service. When firms use a traditional online
platform, they encounter two main drawbacks. First, each transaction
generates a marginal transaction cost, whose impact on the firms’ profits depends on the quantity moved across the SC and/or the good sold.
Second, managing relationships in a classical platform can generate
business risks that firms cannot control during the negotiation process.
The retailer, which is the firm most likely affected by the negative
implications of a tradition online platform, can decide to move to a
blockchain platform. The latter has the main objective of mitigating
the business risks in the SC, making the transactions secure, visible, and
transparent. Furthermore, this allows firms to fully save the transaction
costs existing in traditional negotiations. At the same time, blockchain
applications create new business implications for SCs. On the one hand,
the SC members face costs linked to the blockchain implementation and
management. On the other hand, the SC members gain a number of
tokens (option value) which is exemplified by the translation of information transparency, trust, security, and risk mitigation in economic
terms.
Our findings highlight the detrimental effects that both transaction
costs and business risks can have on SC performance. While the adoption of a blockchain clearly removes these negative effects, firms can
find its implementation and business implications economically inconvenient. The fixed cost for implementing a blockchain is not important
for firms because they can easily adjust their strategies to recover such
investment. Rather, the tokens and the marginal blockchain cost have
important business repercussions with the marginal cost being more
important than the tokens. Therefore, firms implementing a blockchain
should first evaluate the marginal costs: When those are high, the
blockchain should not be implemented because neither the number of
tokens nor the risk and transaction cost mitigation justifies its adoption.
