2. Literature review
Blockchain is a general purpose technology. The latter is defined
as a technology that plays the role of ‘‘enabler’’, opening up new
opportunities rather than offering complete, final solutions (Bresnahan
and Trajtenberg, 1995). Therefore, blockchain is a complementary
innovation since it supports existing innovations to reach goals never
achieved before. Sakoshi Nakamoto was the initiators of blockchain
technology, which was created to support bitcoin transactions and consisted of a distributed database able to maintain a continuously growing
list of records (blocks) from tampering or revision (Nakamoto, 2019).
Previous generations of technologies were most likely about fastening
and securely exchanging of information. Rather, blockchain is about
creating value by enabling firms and individuals to exchange assets
of any kind without relying of third party managing the transactions
(Mulligan et al., 2018).
Blockchain technology can effectively boost the value created in
SCs, in which the transactions occur at a global scale, there is uncertainty on a some operational features (e.g., delivery, last mile management, bullwhip effect), and traditional vendor rating procedures
can be ineffective in finding trusty parties (Babich and Hilary, 2019).
Blockchain enables the reduction of two significant costs that challenge
all supply chains: The cost of verifying the attributes of a transaction
and the cost of exchanging value within a network without relying
on intermediaries (Michelman, 2017). The transaction and verification
costs link to all issues arising when treating a transaction in supply
chain management. Currently, Blockchain can substantially help in this
regards, by allowing the distributed ledger to manage all these tasks,
hence ensuring security and trustworth of suppliers and transactions
(De Giovanni, 2019a). Therefore, blockchain can efficiently manage
all issues linked to settlement and reconciliation that can occur over
supply chains (Catalini and Gans, 2016). For example, blockchain
