not at all superfast (Pournader et al., 2019), allow SC members to
finalize transactions faster than traditional exchange systems (Ivanov
et al., 2019a). Furthermore, blockchains eliminate all intermediate
actors over a certain transaction, leading to considerable cost savings
any time a transaction is carried out, independent of the country,
region, and distance. Hence, blockchains guarantee zero transaction
downtimes thereby ensuring SCs’ synchronization of flows, movements,
and operations (Morkunas et al., 2019).
Clearly, Blockchains are also characterized by several weaknesses
that SCs should consider before diving into such projects:
1. The implementation of blockchain applications requires that all
SC members take into account the complex regulatory, tax, auditability,
risk, and compliance implications linked to any global transaction
platform (Cole et al., 2019). Therefore, SCs need to hire highly skilled
and competent Blockchain developers to project, create, and implement
a blockchain contemplating the earlier mentioned features (Liao et al.,
2017). Accordingly, the implementation cost and time can proportionally increase according to the peculiar context in which the digital
application is supposed to work (Misra, 2018).
2. Blockchains are composed of networks of nodes and blocks.
Hence, when a node must to be processed, the application should
transversally come across all preceding nodes, process all intermediate
nodes, and then reach the target node (Ganeriwalla et al., 2018).
As a result, there is a continuous redundancy of processing nodes,
requiring time, energy, and, consequently, costs (Saberi et al., 2019b).
These implications can even be worsened by the procedure allowing SC
members to reach a consensus. Depending on the SC size as well as the
number of blocks and nodes, blockchains can request intense peer-topeer communications and exchanges to achieve a common consensus
(Büyüközkan and Göçer, 2018).
3. A blockchains consensus limits the total amount of transactions
that SC members can finalize in a given time. Clearly, firms have
opportunities to increase the transaction capacity per unit of time (distributed ledger technology) but this implies additional costs (Hofmann
and Rüsch, 2017). In addition, increasing the number of transactions
also implies rapid expansion of the blockchain size, causing a further
issue of capacity storage. SC members adopting blockchains must need
to define the parties that will manage and govern the distributed ledger
to identify the party responsible for system maintenance and upgrades
(Kshetri, 2018).
In this research, we seek to characterize a game theory model of
SC that embeds positive and negative business implications due to
blockchain. We start our investigation from the implementation and
analysis of a traditional supply chain that uses a conventional online
platform to finalize and manage transactions at a global scale. Then,
the adoption of blockchain technology is evaluated within the same
framework, by addressing the most relevant positive and negative
implications for SCs as emerged from Babich and Hilary (2019), Griffith
(2018) and Gurtu and Johny (2019), as well as by the empirical
research by van Hoek (2019). When applied to SCs, blockchain plays a
key role in enabling the reduction of transaction costs, eliminating of
delivery risks, mitigating of market uncertainty, and creating new value
through tokens. Furthermore, blockchain also implies implementation
investments, learning costs for firms that need to modify business
model, shifting the culture and modus operandi, operational practices and daily procedures. Finally, blockchain enables the adoption of
smart contracts through ethereum, which creates new challenges and
complexity linked to the identification of smart contract clauses and
terms. These features require the engineering of protocols and routines
that artificial intelligence and virtual machines run seeking to execute
procedures, verify conditions, and monitor suppliers’ acceptance and
performance. As explained by Barrera and Catalini (2018), searching
for all these features requires the use of game theory since firms’
interactions, frictions, incentives, objectives, penalties, and behavior
should all be included in the smart contract protocols. The comparison of traditional supply chain platforms with blockchain applications
allow us to highlight the operational and economic advantages of
blockchain technologies and define its boundaries of applications and
future developments.

