The second cost that blockchain aims at removing its the networking
cost, which are very popular in SC management. De Giovanni (2016)
build up on the Transaction Cost Theory by Williamson (1979) and
identify two cost categories that can be removed through blockchain
technology: Bargaining and enforcement costs. Bargaining costs are the
costs required to define an acceptable agreement with the other SC
party to a transaction or drawing up an appropriate contract in global
contexts. Enforcement costs are the costs of making sure the other party
sticks to the contractual terms, exemplified by the costs of controlling and monitoring the SC participants behavior and commitments.
Furthermore, blockchain enables the networking cost reduction by
acting on the cost of bootstrapping, operating, and scaling an economic
network (Catalini and Gans, 2016). Bootstrapping refers to subsidizing
mining via the block reward to get bitcoin to a stage where it is
relatively safe from hash rate related attacks. Operating costs link to the
ability to verify property rights, check the states, and define incentives
without the use of intermediaries. Scaling costs depend on the blocks
size and the block rate, which are inversely linked to the blockchain
security: high size (rate) leads to high (low) security (Greyblock, 2018).
Traditional research in SC management investigates the firms’ transactions and networking by mainly using game theory (cachon, 2003;
De Giovanni, 2009). However, after the advent of bitcoins and
blockchain through Nakamoto’s developments, no research has investigated blockchain technology in SCs using game theory, leaving a
research gap that we intend to fulfill. The current research in SCs linked
to blockchain is purely theoretical and qualitative, that is, it describes
what blockchain is, the possible benefits in operations and SC, the
limitations and barriers, and the future research directions (e.g., Babich
and Hilary (2019), Griffith (2018), Gurtu and Johny (2019); van Hoek
(2019)). Nevertheless, there is no research that evaluates and quantifies
the real benefits of blockchain by identifying and evaluating its positive
and negative implications for SCs. Regarding the points linked to SCs,
firms initiating blockchain projects can pursue the following benefits:
1. Blockchains are decentralized systems without any central authority controlling and supervising the transactions. Therefore, transactions among the SC members are fully visible and quickly exchangeable
without any central administrator permission (Chang et al., 2020).
The idea is that third parties like governments, intermediaries, and
banks are too vulnerable and can be easily attacked. The blockchain
advantages are then exemplified by cost savings of not having to hire
IS experts to prevent, control, and stop cyberattacks and eventually
restore the whole set of functionalities (Kiel et al., 2017).
2. Blockchains allow data, information and transactions to be visible
and transparent (Cole et al., 2019). Any SC member records transactions in the blockchain such that all other SC members can visualize
and keep track of all actions, affairs, and movements (Francisco and
Swanson, 2018). In addition, the records are immutable and unalterable, meaning that SC members’ actions and decisions are all recorded
and documented on the blockchain. When their actions imply good outcomes, all SC members become permanently aware of the correctness of
these actions. Also, when firms’ affairs lead to questionable outcomes
and arguable business implications, SC members keep track of them
and adjust their decisions in finalizing future transactions (Hawlitschek
et al., 2018). Therefore, SC members working through blockchains have
strong incentives to perform the best operations ever (De Giovanni,
2019a). Finally, the recorded transactions are immutable, or at least
they can be modified only when all firms, SC members, and stakeholders involved in the same transaction give their consensus (Kshetri,
2018).
