In this paper, we seek to analyze a simple supply chain (SC) model
with the main goal of evaluating the operational and economic benefits
that SC members can obtain when moving from a traditional platform
to blockchain when making transactions. In this regard, we investigate
an SC that is composed of one supplier, firm 𝑆 (he), and one retailer,
firm 𝑅 (she). The firms negotiate and set their strategies in an online
platform. The supplier is the chain leader and sets a certain amount of
online services, 𝐴, to be delivered. The retailer is the chain follower,
shows a certain willingness to purchase from the supplier and sets
the final price of the products, 𝑝, as well as the number of goods to
purchase, 𝑄. Since the firms work in an online platform, the game
moves according to the following steps:
1. The supplier displays online information about the availability of
goods as well as the selling price, 𝑤, which is assumed to be exogenous.
2. The retailer seeks to purchase from the supplier a certain quantity
𝑄. At the same time, she also decides the optimal selling price, 𝑝, at
which she seeks to sell the goods.
3. The supplier considers the retailer’s strategies and offers a certain
package of online services by investing some efforts, 𝐴.
We assume that the supplier has an infinite production capacity,
works in a make-to-order mode, and is always able to satisfy the
retailer’s requests. The SC can be managed by using two different digital
platforms, either a traditional online marketplace or a blockchain.
We aim to identify the conditions under which the implementation
of a blockchain is operationally and economically convenient. Therefore, we characterize a traditional online marketplace (-game) and
compare it to a blockchain setting (-game).
