According to Proposition 2, the supplier is highly discouraged by
the presence of transaction costs and risks. In fact, his efforts in online
service constantly decrease with the transaction cost and, consequently,
the number of services guaranteed is low as well. This signifies that the
supplier faces important transaction costs that limit sales development.
In fact, the service efforts have a direct and positive connection with
sales. Therefore, the transaction costs may be a considerable deterrent
for the suppliers’ service efforts. In the same vein, the distortion existing
between services and sales pushes the supplier to reduce the efforts
in service. This is mainly linked to the appreciation that consumers
have of the service package offered when the service comes from
online sources. According to Chiang and Dholakia (2003), consumers
have a different perception of the benefits obtainable from online and
offline services since the online service can present issues like long
delivery time and low online services (Abdul-Muhmin, 2010). This is
even more evident when consumers do not fully trust the firm providing
the services and lower their expectations regarding the real services
to be received. This lack of trust translates into a lower amount that
the supplier invests in services, which deteriorates the sales through
the amplitude of 𝜃. Finally, the supplier knows that the transition
between him and the retailer might be not be secure and that the
related uncertainty discourages the SC business. From his side, the
supplier has no practical tool to assure the SC members regarding
security, volatility, and risks of transactions. Therefore, he knows that
all these uncertainties translate into lower appeal for online business
and expects retailers to be less willing to close transactions or to finalize
a transaction with big orders. Therefore, the supplier sets small efforts
for services due to pessimistic forecasts.

