Propositions 3 and 4 inform on the negative implications that downstream firms experience when missing any blockchain application. As
with the supplier, the retailer also faces important transaction costs,
which are a function of both the quantity ordered and the supplier’s
service. In the former case, the transaction cost links to any unit of
goods that is moved over the supply chain; in the latter case, the retailer
faces transaction costs to connect her consumers with the supplier. Consequently, the retailer pays a double bill and the overall convenience
of the costly transaction decreases considerably, with negative effects
on the quantity involved. Interestingly, a generally accepted result in
economics is that decreasing quantity (and then demand) leads to a
price increase, which allows the decision maker to balance quantity
and price. Within the framework that we are modeling, we see that the
price follows the same direction as the quantity ordered. In fact, the
retailer knows that the supplier invests fewer efforts in service, with a
negative impact on sales. This negative impact is then counter-balanced
by a price decrease.
Because the supply chain connections and transactions are not
regulated, the supplier faces a high risk of receiving a lower amount
than the real quantity ordered. Abdul-Muhmin (2010) shows that the
supplier risk for non-regulated online purchasing can considerably
influence firms’ performance. This risk makes the retailer more prudent when deciding the quantity orders leading to lower lot sizes
corroborated by an increase of the connections with different suppliers
(suppliers risk diversification). Under such circumstances, the supplier
might want to ensure a high capital turnover by charging a lower price.
Also, the presence of low quantity on the retailer’s shelf reflects into
a lower level of service, exemplified by the product availability. The
low price seeks to also balance the (scarce) goods availability at an
accessible price.
Finally, the service risk that the retailer experiences has a negative
influence on both the quantity and the price. From the retailer’s side,
this effect implies doubts regarding the supplier and the suspicion that
the service efforts will eventually translate in low consumer satisfaction
and, consequently, low sales. This dubious situation drives the retailer
through the decision to invest less in the business by ordering a lower
final quantity. The intention would probably be to get experience in
working with the supplier before diving into more important and involved connections. Since acquiring trust needs time, no formal tool or
standard ensures the correct order finalization. On the other hand, the
retailer charges low prices to balance the overall inefficiency created
by doubtful orders and uncertain investments in service.

