According to Proposition 8, the retailer exploits the benefits of a
blockchain application in several ways. First, as for the supplier, she
fully removes the uncertainty from the transactions, which then become
trustful and transparent. Therefore, she exploits the benefits of no
transactional risks which are exemplified by purchasing more quantity,
displaying more goods on the shelf to achieve the maximum market
potential, and increasing the price at the same time. This dual effect
contrasts with the general economic trade-off between quantity and
pricing. Nevertheless, our findings depend on the brick-and-mortar SC
that we modeled where the quantity on the shelf determines the market
size. Second, making transactions on a blockchain leads to tokens
through which all firms and stakeholders around the retailer acquire
confidence and trust in developing future business and transactions.
This effect is important for balancing the higher level of confidence
and trust with a larger price. When the transactions are secure, the
consumers have better feelings when purchasing and suppliers become
aware of the supply chain visibility in the transactions.
Note that the retailer should compare the positive effect of tokens to
the cost implications. In fact, the blockchain implies both variable costs
for the retailer (e.g., coding, protocol agreement, number of accesses)
and fixed costs (e.g., cost for implementing the blockchain and integrating it within the IS). Increasing the marginal blockchain transaction
cost harms the retailer’s willingness to implement this technology, the
positive implications of removing the risk terms, as well as the overall
convenience of the purchase. In such cases, increasing the price may
be detrimental since the market will not positively perceive the pricing
policy, although it is generated through transparent, fair, and visible
transactions. In addition, the convenience of purchasing a large amount
of goods through a trustful transaction may not be justified by the
related market expansion. Therefore, the negative cost effects induced
by a blockchain may lead to a discrepancy between the goods displayed
on the shelf and the market potential to be achieved.
In principle, the adoption of a blockchain makes consumers more
secure about the transactions carried out by the firms involved in the
goods’ delivery. The absence of supply chain and delivery risks makes
products more available on the shelf, leading consumers to have higher
accessibility and goods availability. Furthermore, the absence of a
service risk makes consumers more comfortable with the entire package
of post-sale services, which increases their confidence in the purchase
and their willingness to purchase more. At the same time, these higher
levels of services imply higher prices for consumers. Therefore, overall,
the implementation of a blockchain does not necessarily lead to a sales
increase. Rather, firms need to balance the higher efforts needed for
adopting this new technology with the potential negative implications
for the demand.

