The adoption of a blockchain brings positive and negative news
for firms. On the one hand, the blockchain fully removes the risk
in purchasing and service, leading to high transparency on the real
transactions occurring over the supply chain and mutual enhancement
of trust. The latter can be quantified through an option value (tokens),
which represents the future benefits that the companies will acquire
after managing their business through the blockchain. For example,
firms and stakeholders will know on the true quantity that has been
moved in transactions, the real amount of investments in services,
and the market prices for the goods exchanged. On the other hand,
the blockchain carries some fixed costs due to its implementation and
integration with the current IS. Furthermore, it still implies transaction
costs that link to consensus protocols, transaction size and volume,
cloud costs, and node hosting. All these trade-offs can make the adoption of a blockchain economically inconvenient and raise the questions
regarding the extent to which this technology really works. Clearly,
in the particular case when 𝑐𝐵 = 0, the firms’ strategies and sales
