5. Comparison between the -game and -game
To appreciate the benefits of a blockchain, we carry out a numerical analysis on the key parameters. The two games differ along six
parameters, specifically, 𝛾, 𝜙, 𝑐𝑇 , 𝑐𝐵 , 𝐹 , and 𝑣, with 𝛾 and 𝜙 describing
some stochastic components and, consequently, the retailer’s risks for
purchasing and service. To properly compare the solutions and derive
managerial insights, we fix the parameter values for 𝛾 = 0.01, 𝜙 =
0.01, and 𝑐𝑇 = 0.05, whose effects have been checked analytically in
Section 3. We then focus on the remaining three parameters: 𝑣, 𝑐𝐵 , and
𝐹 . In addition, the other parameters have been fixed as follows: 𝛼 = 0.9,
𝛽 = 1, 𝜃 = 1, 𝜔 = 0.8, 𝑐𝑆 = 0.02, 𝑐𝑅 = 0.02, 𝑐𝐴 = 0.05, 𝑐𝑄 = 0.05,
𝜆𝑆 = 0.01, and 𝜆𝑅 = 0.01. To fix these parameters, we referred to
real estimations linked to business reports (e.g., EY, 2019), secondary
information available (Azati, 2019), empirical estimations reported in
the literature (e.g., van Hoek, 2019; Hackius and Petersen, 2017) as
well as the parameter estimations from the literature of game theory
(e.g., Genc and De Giovanni, 2020). By fixing these parameters, we
ensure that all conditions that we have previously introduced are met
and that both games are feasible.

5.2. Quantity, price and sales
Fig. 2 shows the behavior of the retailer’s order quantity and price,
as well as the sales that she obtains. Although these three are measured
in different scales (vertical dimension), the comparison over the two
games shows equivalent shapes. The main difference with respect to
Fig. 1 is on the amplitude of the -game outcomes over the -game
outcomes. Accordingly, the retailer gains more confidence than the
supplier when implementing a blockchain, which translates into higher
purchasing quantity. Intuitively, this quantity is positively (negatively)
influenced by token 𝑣 (marginal blockchain cost 𝑐𝐵 ). The high trust and
confidence that the retailer obtains through the blockchain have immediate links and benefits for sales, as all business risks are effectively
removed from the decision-making process. In addition, the retailer
enjoys the absence of transaction costs linked to the use of traditional
online platforms. Although the adoption of blockchains removes several
inefficiencies linked to a traditional supply chain and transactions, the
inefficient installation and management of blockchains can limit the
firms’ willingness to adopt this type of project. The existence of fixed
and variable costs deriving from blockchain applications makes the
benefits very small. In fact, the traditional transaction cost might simply
be substituted by the blockchain cost, with the result that the project
could appear marginally appealing. While the risk mitigation is a clear
advantage, the existence of additional blockchain costs means that
retailers charge higher prices, with the result that the products become
less appealing to consumers. As a consequence, retailers purchase less
quantity, demonstrating that the business is marginally worthy. This
perception becomes a real issue for the supplier, who invests less in

