7. Smart contracts in blockchains
In this section, we explore two options available for the SC to
pursue a blockchain project while allowing some contract terms to be
automatically adjusted by a Virtual Machine or/and an Artificial Intelligence (AI) (De Giovanni, 2019a). Smart contracts, which use ethereum
for a proper implementation, allow self-executing scripts that reside
on the blockchain, leading to an integration of these concepts within
the SC negotiations and allowing for proper, distributed, and heavily automated workflows (Christidis and Devetsikiotis, 2016). Raskin
(2017) defines a smart contract as an agreement wherein execution
is automated by a computer that ensures performance and execution
without recourse to the courts and mitigating any human discretion.
Therefore, a smart contract is a computer protocol intended to digitally facilitate, verify, and enforce the negotiation or performance of
a contract (Szabo, 1994). Proponents of smart contracts claim that
many kinds of contractual clauses may be made partially or fully selfexecuting, self-enforcing, or both (Brown, 2015), and can be based on
both forward and reverse activities (De Giovanni and Zaccour, 2019b).
Considering the framework under investigation we propose two smart
contracts: a smart wholesale price contract and a smart revenue sharing
contract. To activate these two contracts, blockchain technology needs
to be connected to the eco-system by using oracles. These are drivers
that allow firms to move from the physical world to the digital world
and solve off-line operational issues like the first mile and the last
mile. The oracles can be of several types: Hardware oracles (data from
physical world), software oracles (data from online world), human
oracles (consensus for data validation), inbound oracles (external data
as input for the smart contract), and outbound oracles (smart contract
as an input for the external world). The oracles take information from
the physical world, create and adjust incentives for every undertaken
action, and distribute tokens and/or cryptocurrencies through the smart
contracts and according to the information exchange.

