Therefore, managers can properly assess the real benefits of blockchains
only when a correct comparison between the cost savings from traditional transactions and the business risk mitigation generate more value
than the blockchain implementation and management. Furthermore,
managers should also spend some time to quantify the tokens granted
by a blockchain. This is exemplified by, for example, the trust that
the firm gains within the SC, the knowledge of the other companies’
behavior and performance, the visibility of all operations, and the
warranty to always perform to consumers’ expectations. These (soft)
features gained through a blockchain are not immediately quantifiable;
however, managers should assign a value to the single knowledge
creation piece acquired through the use of the blockchain to properly
evaluate its implementation.
3. Beyond transaction costs and investments, managers should carefully evaluate the impact of business risks on their economic performance. The service risks have a marginal impact on the decision to
implement a blockchain. This is most likely linked to the information
flows that consumers generate through online systems, social networks,
and sharing platforms, which allow firms to update their strategies
accordingly. Differently, the delivery risks are more dangerous for SC
management; therefore, managers should properly map all business
risks associated to the delivery process and setup a blockchain system
that considers and optimizes all of them.
4. The ‘‘pure’’ adoption of a blockchain cannot be very appealing,
especially from an economic point of view. That is, investing in a
blockchain only to gain transparency, visibility, and security while
getting rid of transaction costs and business risks may not be sufficient
to justify the implementation of blockchain technology. In such circumstances, we suggest that managers look at smart contract parameters
to be modified autonomously by the Blockchain. One of the most
interesting parameters that blockchains can modify in our setting is
the wholesale price. Therefore, once the blockchain becomes operative,
the wholesale price is determined by the AI rather than be predefined.
Clearly, the blockchain is able to generate the wholesale price variation
that is needed to increase firms’ willingness to use Blockchains. For example, the retailer should give a higher wholesale price to the supplier
. Specifically, a 25% increment in the wholesale price leads the supplier
to be willing to use blockchains while granting an 18% increase in
the retailer’s profits. Hence, using a smart wholesale price gives a true
chance to gain all benefits linked to blockchain technologies.
5. Although the smart wholesale price works well to make the
blockchain function, the wholesale price increase can be considered
as to be too high and retailers can be reluctantly to move forward
with blockchains. Thus, we suggest that managers complement the
blockchain technology with a smart RSC. In such a case, the AI of
the blockchain determines the fraction of the retailer’s revenues to be
transferred to the supplier to make it willing to use the new digital
platform. Our results indicate that a share of 2.5% already gives sufficient economic incentive to the supplier to use the blockchain, while
generating a 110% increase in the supplier’s profit. Differently from the
smart wholesale price, the smart RSC makes the supplier responsible

8. Managerial insights
This section offers managerial insights, which can help managers
better evaluate whether to pursue a project based on blockchain technologies. The managerial insights can be summarized in four main
points, as detailed below:
1. Managers should look at investments in blockchain technologies
when the transaction costs over the SC are high and when the related
business risks are high as well. Among all constellations of business
risks that exist in nature, we focus on two: The delivery risks and
the service risks. Both have a negative impact on firms’ business and
the whole SC efficiency. Therefore, when one of those features takes
a high value, firms should evaluate the implementation, integration,
and use of blockchains along with their current IS. Firms can expect
both operational advantages and economic gains. The operational improvements link to: (a) better consumer service and, hence, level of
service, (b) increasing the competitive position through a wider market
offer and increasing sales (with market share implications as well),
and (c) the possibility to charge higher final prices and, consequently,
extract more economic value from the market. The pricing strategy does
not discourage consumers from purchasing thanks to the compensating
effect of better services and market presence.
2. Managers should be aware that blockchains are not free. They
carry costs for installing and integrating them in firms’ current IS.
There are also additional marginal (variable) costs to consider, such as
