transaction costs and the business risks of a traditional online platform
with the variable blockchain cost. The firms’ strategies and policies can
always be set to overcome the limits of the initial investments, while
the number of tokens alone is not sufficient to justify the adoption of
a blockchain. Furthermore, the transaction costs and the business risks
of traditional platforms have a considerable impact on the blockchain’s
economic advantages. Specifically, when the transaction costs and/or
the business risks are negligible, the adoption of blockchains is operationally inefficient and economically not appealing. Our simulations
demonstrate that the delivery risks have more prominent effects than
service risks. The latter can be mitigated by a traditional online platform in most of the cases, being detrimental only for volatility higher
than 20%. In contrast, the delivery risk has considerable effect on both
firms profits. Delivery risk of 10% suggests to implement blockchain
technology. We demonstrate that the blockchain should request a smart
wholesale price to overcome these limitations. In particular, the retailer
can offer a (minimum) wholesale price increase of 25% to improve its
profits of 18% while allowing the supplier to gain the same amount of
money as in an online platform. Therefore, the smart wholesale price
allows the SC to achieve a profit-Pareto-improving situation and make
the blockchain successful.
Although the smart wholesale price can be a good incentive for
suppliers to work and finalize transactions on a blockchain, having the
retailer offering a 25% wholesale price increase may imply huge investments for her side. This insight leaves rooms to complement blockchain
applications with a smart RSC. Based on the previous statements, the
blockchain alone is not always convenient even if it generates a smart
contract based on a classical wholesale price mechanism. Therefore,
we evaluate the existence of an AI supporting the blockchain that
adds new features to the negotiations and that proposes a smart RSC.
In contrast to the smart wholesale price, which is a pure monetary
incentive based on the quantity that the retailer orders, the smart RSC
incentivizes the supplier in two ways: First, it proposes a share of
the retailer’s revenues coming on top of its profits; second, the smart
RSC makes the supplier responsible for the retailer’s revenue growth
by acting through the services. Our analysis demonstrates that the
supplier can offer a minimum 2.5% share to increase its profits of
110%, while ensuring to the supplier a profit as in an online platform.
Therefore, blockchain technologies complemented with smart RSC are
more successful than both traditional online platforms and blockchains
based on smart wholesale contracts.
