9. Conclusions
This paper investigates the operational and economic advantages
that firms in a supply chain (SC) can obtain when managing their
businesses through a blockchain rather than using traditional online
platforms. We analyze a simple brick-and-mortar SC composed of one
supplier and one retailer. The use of a traditional online platform
carries both transaction costs and business risks. The former is linked to
the management of global SC connections, requiring several intermediaries, governmental constraints, and cultural differences. The latter
refer to the supply and delivery risks, which are not manageable by
SC members, as well as by the service risks, linked to the real services
provided by global suppliers differing from the original expectations.
These weaknesses can lead the traditional online platforms to inefficient negotiations and risky businesses. All SC members adjust their
strategic behavior accordingly: The supplier invests the lowest possible
efforts in services, which may find very low appreciation by partners
and consumers, especially in a global context; also, the retailer orders
smaller quantity batches and sets lower prices since the overall business
is strategically unappealing and highly risky.
SCs can effectively overcome these negative issues through the
implementation of a blockchain application. The blockchain has several
good features (see Cole et al. (2019) for a comprehensive analysis),
among which the information visibility, transparency, and security
allow both the transaction costs and the supply and service risks to
be fully mitigated. As with all Industry 4.0 technologies and digital
transformation projects, blockchains imply undoubted drawbacks. In
the particular SC framework that we model, SCs seeking to implement
blockchains face fixed costs (e.g., investments for hiring IS experts) as
well as variable costs (e.g., time and energy consumed when running
complex blockchain networks). Hence, firms and SCs need to evaluate the negative implications of traditional online platforms with the
blockchain inefficiency, along with the possible tokens and option value
that the blockchain may imply. The latter refers to the gains in terms
of trust, visibility and knowledge over the entire business, which allow
decision makers to better adjust their strategies and define the most
valuable policies. According to all these ingredients, our findings suggest that SCs have operational and economic motivations to implement
blockchains when the variable cost due to the technology adoption,
implementation, integration and usage is not too high. In contrast, the
blockchain fixed cost and token value only have a marginal impact
