whether our findings can be generalized. Furthermore, future research
can investigate the implications of other chain structures and check
how different power structures and leadership positions can affect
the results. This direction can be corroborated by endogenizing some
ingredients that we considered as exogenous in this research, like the
wholesale price and the fix cost for the blockchain implementation.
Our blockchain model is composed of one block only, consisting of
the transaction between the supplier and the retailer. Future research
can look at the existence of more blocks and, consequently, more firms
interacting within the SC, to see how the blockchain implications linked
to the consensus affect its suitability. For example, future research
can use the framework that we analyze as a benchmark and evaluate
it within some specific settings, like, Walmart and Dole, which we
mention in the introduction. We assume that the retailer covers the
entire cost for implementing a blockchain since she is most likely
affected by unsecure transactions. Future work can look at the area of
collaborative planning and SC coordination to establish collaborative
programs among firms pursuing blockchain projects. One interesting
feature of a blockchain is that it allows the SC to accumulate knowledge
over time and use this knowledge in the decision-making process.
Future research can then look at dynamic modeling where firms using
a blockchain accumulate knowledge through a dynamic equation and
exploit it when dynamically setting their strategies. We focus our analysis on service, pricing and quantity, while other ingredients like lead
time, quality, R&D, advertising, and location (just to mention a few)
can be further considered to investigate the blockchain’s advantages.
These features can lead to the analysis of new smart contracts
based on quantity (e.g., quantity discount), pricing (e.g., minimum suggested price), sales (e.g., sales rebate), or performance
achievements (e.g., strategic incentives). Future research can also
look at testing the results of this research through empirical studies or
through clinical cases. We have based parameter estimations, simulations, and framework according to a theoretical setting. Future research
can start the analysis of blockchain from a case study, develop the
parameter estimations accordingly, and run simulations within that
particular framework. The blockchain is only one technology linked to
the current digital transformation that has been analyzed. Other technologies (e.g., Industry 4.0) can complement our findings to investigate
the synergistic effects among them. This is a current research theme
that the authors are exploring.

